    "long_instructions": "# Do This:\r\n1. **Run and observe** <br>\r\n2. **Modify:** Comment out the conditional (lines 11-17) and uncomment the `move_if_can()` function on lines 19-25. <br>\r\n3. **Discuss:** What do you think will happen when you call the function with a `north` argument? What will the painter do? Give a try!\r\n4. **Test and Run:** Call the function a with different directions as the argument (e.g. `move_if_can(\"west\")`, `move_if_can(\"east\")`, etc).\r\n    <br>\r\n- **Discuss:**\r\n\t- How does the function simplify controlling the Painter’s movement?\r\n\t- Why does the Painter skip moving if the condition is false?\r\n",
    "start_sources": {
      "files": {
        "0": {
          "id": "0",
          "name": "main.py",
          "language": "py",
          "contents": "from neighborhood import Painter\n\n#add the painter object below\nryan = Painter()\n\n# take all the paint\nwhile ryan.is_on_bucket():\n  ryan.take_paint()\n\n# conditional statements\nif ryan.can_move(\"south\"):\n  ryan.move()\n  ryan.paint(\"blue\")\n\nif ryan.can_move(\"south\"):\n  ryan.move()\n  ryan.paint(\"blue\")\n\n#def move_if_can(direction):\n#  if painter.can_move(direction):\n#    painter.move()\n#    painter.paint(\"blue\")\n\n# move_if_can('south')\n# move_if_can('south')\n",
          "folderId": "0",
          "active": true,
          "open": true
        }
      },
      "folders": {
      }
    },
